{"primaryContentSections":[{"declarations":[{"tokens":[{"text":"protocol","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"ThrowingPropertyWrapper","kind":"identifier"},{"text":"<","kind":"text"},{"text":"Value","identifier":"doc:\/\/Thrappture\/documentation\/Thrappture\/ThrowingPropertyWrapper\/Value","preciseIdentifier":"s:10Thrappture23ThrowingPropertyWrapperP5ValueQa","kind":"typeIdentifier"},{"text":", ","kind":"text"},{"text":"Error","identifier":"doc:\/\/Thrappture\/documentation\/Thrappture\/ThrowingPropertyWrapper\/Error","preciseIdentifier":"s:10Thrappture23ThrowingPropertyWrapperP5ErrorQa","kind":"typeIdentifier"},{"text":">","kind":"text"}],"languages":["swift"],"platforms":["macOS"]}],"kind":"declarations"},{"kind":"content","content":[{"type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"overview","text":"Overview"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In addition to what can be represented in the type system,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"there are many methods which all "},{"code":"ThrowingPropertyWrapper","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"s have in common,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"which vary only by the generic representation of "},{"code":"Self","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":", with various "},{"code":"Value","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" and "},{"code":"Error","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" types."},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"See the documentation for a list of those “requirements”."}]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Requirements","text":"“Requirements”"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Below, you’ll find implementations of similar methods on ","type":"text"},{"code":"Optional","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" and ","type":"text"},{"code":"Result","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":". Their “mapping” methods warrant more details:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","level":5,"anchor":"General-transformation","text":"General transformation"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Transforming a value, by applying a function to it using dot syntax, is sometimes an easier-to-read way to write code, and probably ought to be available on "},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"every type","type":"text"}]},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["func transform<Transformed, Error>(","  _ transform: (Self) throws(Error) -> Transformed",") throws(Error) -> Transformed {","  try transform(self)","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"But that’s not specific to throwing property wrappers, and is not included in this package."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"We "},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"could","type":"text"}]},{"type":"text","text":" restrict the transformation to require mapping similar types of wrappers, such as "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Int?"},{"type":"text","text":" ➡️ "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"String?"},{"type":"text","text":", or "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Result<Int, Never>"},{"type":"text","text":" ➡️ "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Result<String, any Error>"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"heading","level":6,"anchor":"Result","text":"Result"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"For ","type":"text"},{"code":"Result","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":", that would look like this:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["func transform<NewSuccess, NewFailure, Error>(","  _ transform: (Self) throws(Error) -> Result<NewSuccess, NewFailure>",") throws(Error) -> Result<NewSuccess, NewFailure> {","  try transform(self)","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"heading","level":6,"anchor":"Optional","text":"Optional"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"And ","type":"text"},{"code":"Optional","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":"’s equivalent implementation would look like this:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["func transform<NewWrapped, Error>(","  _ transform: (Self) throws(Error) -> NewWrapped?",") throws(Error) -> NewWrapped? {","  try transform(self)","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Even with this new restriction, the possibilities are so vast in what can be accomplished there, that it’s not worth creating a function for. And so again, this "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"transform"},{"type":"text","text":" is not included in this package either."}]},{"type":"heading","level":3,"anchor":"flatMap","text":"flatMap"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"code":"flatMap","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" is the closest to a general-purpose ","type":"text"},{"code":"transform","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" method that this package works with. The capabilities are different in only two respects:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"orderedList","items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"code":"flatMap","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":"‘s’ ","type":"text"},{"code":"transform","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" closure operates only on a wrapped value, instead of an entire wrapper instance.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"flatMap"},{"type":"text","text":" cannot modify the wrapped error type."}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The “","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"flat"},{"text":"” in ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"flatMap"},{"text":" refers to the way that it introduces no more “nesting” than the wrapper represented before transformation. For example, ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"String?.flatMap"},{"text":", when supplied with a ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"transform"},{"text":" closure returning type ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Int?"},{"text":", will return ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Int?"},{"text":". (As opposed to ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Int??"},{"text":").","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"code":"flatMap","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" will not throw an error when the wrapper wraps an error, but it will throw an error if the transformation throws an error."}]},{"type":"heading","level":6,"anchor":"Result","text":"Result"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"overridingTitleInlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Result"},{"type":"text","text":"’s implementation"}],"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/Thrappture\/documentation\/Thrappture\/Swift\/Result\/flatMap(_:)","isActive":true,"overridingTitle":"Result’s implementation"},{"type":"text","text":" is documented below. The standard library nearly gets this right, but "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/swift\/result\/flatMap(_:)","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"heading","level":6,"anchor":"Optional","text":"Optional"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/swift\/optional\/flatmap(_:)","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" is implemented perfectly in the standard library."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/docs.swift.org\/swift-book\/documentation\/the-swift-programming-language\/optionalchaining\/","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" represents a specific subset of "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"flatMap"},{"type":"text","text":"—the most common use case. It would be great if other throwing property wrappers could use chaining as well, but is of course not supported."}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["let animals: Optional = \"🦁🐯🐻\"","var first: Character? = animals.flatMap(\\.first)","first = animals?.first"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"heading","level":3,"anchor":"flatMapAndMergeError","text":"flatMapAndMergeError"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"This is a special case of ","type":"text"},{"code":"flatMap","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":". If ","type":"text"},{"code":"transform","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" throws the untransformed wrapper’s ","type":"text"},{"code":"Error","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" type, the error can be forwarded into the transformed wrapper type, rather than being thrown from ","type":"text"},{"code":"flatMap","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Both forms are useful. Naming this differently than ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"flatMap"},{"text":" is necessary because it would not be enough, for the compiler, to just add ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"try"},{"text":" in front of another ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"flatMap"},{"text":" overload.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","level":6,"anchor":"Result","text":"Result"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"isActive":true,"overridingTitle":"Result’s implementation","type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/Thrappture\/documentation\/Thrappture\/Swift\/Result\/flatMapAndMergeError(_:)","overridingTitleInlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Result"},{"type":"text","text":"’s implementation"}]},{"type":"text","text":" is documented below."}]},{"type":"heading","level":6,"anchor":"Optional","text":"Optional"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"We’ve defined "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Optional"},{"type":"text","text":"’s "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Error"},{"type":"text","text":" type as "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/Thrappture\/documentation\/Thrappture\/Swift\/Optional\/Nil","isActive":true,"type":"reference","overridingTitle":"Nil","overridingTitleInlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Nil"}]},{"type":"text","text":". But regardless of how you model it, "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Optional.none"},{"type":"text","text":" is generic over "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Optional"},{"type":"text","text":" itself. That means that the only way for two "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Optional"},{"type":"text","text":" types to “share their "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Error"},{"type":"text","text":" type”, is for the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Optional"},{"type":"text","text":"s to actually be of the exact same type."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"So, "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"flatMapAndMergeError"},{"type":"text","text":" would be simplifiable to the following. We haven’t felt a need to include this in this package, but are open to doing so if you could convince us of its usefulness."}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["func flatMapAndMergeError(","  _ transform: (Wrapped) throws(Nil) -> Self",") -> Self {","  try? transform(get())","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"heading","level":3,"anchor":"map","text":"map"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The only difference between "},{"code":"flatMap","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" and "},{"code":"map","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" is that map’s "},{"code":"transform","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" closure returns a wrapped value, not a wrapper. Thusly, no “flattening” is necessary."}]},{"type":"heading","level":6,"anchor":"Result","text":"Result"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"identifier":"doc:\/\/Thrappture\/documentation\/Thrappture\/Swift\/Result\/map(_:)","isActive":true,"type":"reference","overridingTitle":"Result’s implementation","overridingTitleInlineContent":[{"code":"Result","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":"’s implementation","type":"text"}]},{"text":" is documented below. The standard library nearly gets this right, but ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/swift\/result\/map(_:)","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","level":6,"anchor":"Optional","text":"Optional"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/swift\/optional\/map(_:)","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" is implemented perfectly in the standard library."}]},{"type":"heading","level":3,"anchor":"mapAndMergeError","text":"mapAndMergeError"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"This is to ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"map"},{"text":" as ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"flatMapAndMergeError"},{"text":" is to ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"flatMap"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","level":6,"anchor":"Result","text":"Result"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"overridingTitle":"Result’s implementation","overridingTitleInlineContent":[{"code":"Result","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"’s implementation"}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/Thrappture\/documentation\/Thrappture\/Swift\/Result\/mapAndMergeError(_:)","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"text":" is documented below.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","level":6,"anchor":"Optional","text":"Optional"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Because Swift allows for values to be implicitly promoted to optionals, the body of "},{"code":"Optional.mapAndMergeError","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" would be exactly the same as "},{"code":"Optional.flatMapAndMergeError","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":"‘s’, above. So we’re not including this method either."}]},{"type":"heading","level":4,"anchor":"flatMapError","text":"flatMapError"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This is the same idea as "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"flatMap"},{"type":"text","text":", except, with a transformation of the wrapper’s "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Error"},{"type":"text","text":" type, rather than its "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Value"},{"type":"text","text":" type."}]},{"type":"heading","level":6,"anchor":"Result","text":"Result"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"As we’ve seen above with ","type":"text"},{"code":"flatMap","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" and ","type":"text"},{"code":"map","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":", the standard library nearly gets this right, but ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/swift\/result\/mapError(_:)","type":"reference"},{"text":". It ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"should"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"text":", for completeness, but does anyone need that? 🤔 (It won’t be included in this package until we hear that they do.)","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","level":6,"anchor":"Optional","text":"Optional"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Optional"},{"type":"text","text":" cannot make use of this by itself, because its "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Error"},{"type":"text","text":" type always matches its "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Wrapped"},{"type":"text","text":" type. I.e. transforming one "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Optional.Nil"},{"type":"text","text":" to another is the same as transforming one "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Optional"},{"type":"text","text":" to another–it requires a "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"flatMap"},{"type":"text","text":". And, a transformation of "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"nil"},{"type":"text","text":", if you want to do anything other than change one "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"nil"},{"type":"text","text":" into "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"another"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"You can’t do much meaningful using "},{"code":"nil","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" as an input, but there is syntactical sugar available to “transform it”—the "},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/docs.swift.org\/swift-book\/documentation\/the-swift-programming-language\/basicoperators\/#Nil-Coalescing-Operator"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[